    "summary": "Since January 2021 Honorary Professor Organic Agriculture at Madan Bhandari University of Science and Technolgy in Nepal. Consultant to the Asian Development Bank for MBUST University on the development of a Master and PhD program in Organic Agriculture.\n\n2015-2022 Advisor to the Nordic Council of Ministers on sustainable development of the Arctic. Nordforsk Science Program.\n\nI studied physical geography, soil science and planning at the University of Amsterdam from 1973 to 1980. I worked at the Institute for Environmental Studies at the Vrije Universiteit (Free University) in Amsterdam from 1982 to 1989 where I specialized in ecology and the effects of trade on the environment. From 1990 to 1991 I was assistant professor physical geography at the University of Amsterdam. I worked at the Institute of Public Health and the Environment in Bilthoven, the Netherlands from 1991 to 1996 where I was responsible for the national greenhouse gas emissions inventories for the National Communication on Climate Policies from the Netherlands to the Climate Convention. I am a member of the IPCC and consultant to the OECD. I contributed to the IPCC Guidelines for national GHG inventories. During 2005 and 2006 I was coordinating lead author for agriculture and forestry in the 2006 IPCC Guidelines and as such contributed to the Nobel Peace Prize 2007 for IPCC and Al Gore. \n\nFrom 1996 to 2020 I was assistant professor at the Wageningen University, at the Environmental Systems Analysis Group. My main interest is methane and the run away greenhouse effect, and quality control of GHG emissions estimates. I was study advisor for the Master courses Environmental Sciences, Urban Environmental Management and Climate Studies at Wageningen University. The Master Environmental Sciences is rated one of the best Master courses in the Netherlands by the students.\n\nSpecialties: geography, soil science, planning, greenhouse gas emissions, methane, IMAGE model, climate change mitigation and adaptation in Nepal, Bangladesh and India",
